This January we will be offering a Hand to Hand online training program. It will include videos describing each pose and what details we look for to call it ‘complete’.

New Year = 12 Days of Handstand Original Challenge! 
Cumulative Holds

This year we will be practicing Plank or Freestanding Handstands. Once you choose your level, you will hold 1 minute per day of the month.

  Day 1 = 1 min
  Day 2 = 2 min
  Day 3 = 3 min... ... ... until
  Day 12 = 12 min

These are cumulative minutes. Meaning that you will start a timer as soon your feet leave the ground and stop the timer as soon as your feet return. On you next handstand you will continue the timer until you accumulate your desired time. 

Our biggest advice is:
Do not worry about day 12!

On day one, focus on day one and only day one. On they two focus on day two. Stay focused on the present moment and have fun exploring how to be upside down.

A very soft and hesitant cartwheel entrance into handstands. My very first solid success! 

Cartwheels were never my thing. When I was in elementary school I remember friends effortlessly cartwheeling around the playground. Like gravity had no effect on them. I tried a few times at school and what felt like hundreds of times at the beach. Never really succeeding. Until, I never tried again. 

As an adult I found them so challenging and awkward. Plus they came with a weird self confidence judgment… a fear that my inner child would be exposed. Showing my awful cartwheels meant to me, showing off that I fail at childhood. 

Then I started practicing acro and one day @agustinyoga invited me to cartwheel into a pose. And I said yes. Like I knew how to do it. And he caught - what I can know imagine being an awful cartwheel! But it didn’t matter. He made me feel supported, capable and opened a door to more cartwheels into my life. 

And since then, my inner child rejoices every time my cartwheels seem like gravity has been turned off. Even when my external expression is calmed, inside, mini me is going: wow, you did that! 🥰🤸🏽‍♀️🎉

I love practicing handstands on a paddleboard. They remind me of being a beginner. The fears, the doubts, the lack of control - all of it - returns. My legs have to work so hard to compensate from my body not allowing itself to go upside down, that the next day, my one leg (on the one side I dare to try over and over) is so sore! My mind often wants to give up. Yet at the same time, it wants to persevere. 

I love it… 
I fear it… 
I enjoy the challenge and 
Celebrate every micro second hold. 

The water seems to be a reflection of life. Sometimes wavy. Sometimes quiet. The handstand and the water not always agree on what’s easier. 

Sometimes calm water bring great handstand. Sometimes handstands feel easier on uneasy water. It seems to be a case of the mind choosing to ride that moment. And of the water being deep enough for my mind to fear one less thing. 

Maybe that’s the trick. Let me fall hard. But don’t let me hit the rocky ground.

I recently read a quote that really resonated with me. It said something on the line of ‘If you only train when the environment is perfect and push only when things go well, you are training to quit when faced with adversity.’ 

Which seems true! However, it’s also important to know when to push and when to stop, and to set yourself up for success, keeping in mind what success means to you.

For us, success this day meant having some fun at the beach. We were mainly focused on laughing and smiling together, rather than nailing every pose perfectly. Of course, we still challenged ourselves and worked to improve, but we kept the bigger picture in mind.

Which was…

🌟 Level up your slackline training with these four transitions! 🌟

1️⃣ Knee to Stand Circles: Challenge your balance and strength as you gracefully move from a kneeling position to standing. This transition will enhance your control and stability on the line.

2️⃣ Ground-based Exposure Entrances: It is not common to enter exposure this way. Practicing this technique will prepare you for future exposure transitions.

3️⃣ Assym Sit to Malasana Squat: Combines asymmetrical sitting with a deep Malasana squat. This transition will not only boost your balance, but it will also improve your overall  flexibility.

4️⃣ Exposure Single Leg Balance: Single-leg stability on the slackline helps improve core strength and refines proprioception. Great for slacklining, acro and life! 

🌿 Short and tight lines are fantastic for training, especially if you’re accustomed to longer, looser lines. They offer a unique challenge and can help you fine-tune your teaching skills before working with beginners.

✨ Handstand Challenge ✨
Join our supportive handstand community and transform your handstands training into a fun, monthly practice. This challenge is more than just a New Year Resolution - it’s a continuous journey of strength, balance, and confidence.

During 11 months of the year - the 12 Days of Handstand Program offers a diverse range of strength and balance drills, but during January, we focus on challenging our mental and physical skills by only working on unassisted handstands in the center of the room.

Yep. That means no walls, no spotters!
Although, you can practice Plank Holds as an alternative 🌟

📅 The 12 Days of Handstand Challenge = Hold 1 minute per day of the month.
 Day 1 = 1 min
  Day 2 = 2 min
  Day 3 = 3 min... ... ... until
  Day 12 = 12 min

These are cumulative minutes. Meaning that you will start a timer as soon your feet leave the ground and stop the timer as soon as your feet return. On you next handstand you will continue the timer until you accumulate your desired time. 

👉 Remember: Start small, focus on today, and build trust in your body.
